  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Metaphor is a figure of speech in which one thing is described in terms of another — not as comparison (that is simile) but as identification. \u0026ldquo;The road was a ribbon of moonlight\u0026rdquo; does not say the road resembles a ribbon; it says the road is a ribbon, and the reader holds both terms simultaneously.\nAristotle considered metaphor the mark of genius — \u0026ldquo;the one thing that cannot be learnt from others\u0026rdquo; — because it requires perceiving similarity between dissimilar things [@aristotle_poetics]. This overstates the case; metaphor is a learnable craft skill. But the insight is sound: metaphor works by connecting domains that don\u0026rsquo;t obviously belong together, and the surprise of the connection is part of its meaning.\n",
